:::summary
Ramesses II (c. 1303–1213 BC), known as Ramesses the Great, was the most powerful and celebrated pharaoh of ancient Egypt — a ruler whose 66-year reign saw extraordinary military campaigns, monumental building projects, and diplomatic achievements that set the standard for all subsequent Egyptian pharaohs. Many scholars identify him as the pharaoh of the Exodus, making him one of the most significant rulers in biblical history.
:::

